<TITLE> Markets burst clear of losses </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 12 (bdnews24.com)Banks and insurers fired markets to squirm around losses over weeks on Tuesday, with just about 60 percent of the scrips traded on the twin bourses going up. Market observers said the rise was only natural after days of gloomy trend. "It is quite natural to see a hike like this. Investors indulged in buying in the wake of lower prices," said investment consultant Bashir Ahmed of brokerage firm Stocks & Bonds. The underperformers continued to rise with more than 50 percent of the Z category issues gaining and experts said it was an ominous sign. DSE's former chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed told bdnews24.com that there might be a possibility that "gambling quarters" were trying to make a move. "Market authorities should watch the issue closely," said Ahmed, who now teaches finance at the University of Dhaka. Banks, insurers, non-banking financial institutions and leather-footwear shares topped the buying basket, according to brokerage house officials. "Some other issues rose discretely on rumours of healthy corporate declarations," an official of brokerage house Anwar Securities said, asking not to be named. Mutual funds closed mixed while power shares continued to slip. ICT, energy and fuel shares lost after Monday's gains. Meanwhile, bigwigs in pharmaceuticals jumped. DSE's benchmark general index or DGEN moved upward across the day. It ended higher by 32.12 points or 1.28 percent to 2528.17. The DSI or all share price index finished at 2104.70, gaining 24.37 points or 1.17 percent. The blue-chip DSE-20 rose 17.80 points or 0.92 percent to finish on 1940.40. Gainers outnumbered losers 146 to 92 while 10 issues remained unchanged. Turnover on the country's premier bourse, however, slipped to Tk 4.05 billion from Monday's Tk 4.24 billion. Summit Power was the turnover leader with shares worth Tk 395.092 million traded. It lost 2.77 percent to Tk 1330.75. Beximco followed with a turnover of Tk 294.753 million to edge down 0.32 percent to Tk 273.90. Titas Gas ended on Tk 531.25, down by 1.80 percent. It had shares worth Tk 270.236 million changing hands. Eastern Housing Ltd had Tk 201.404 million in turnover and ended on Tk 737.75, up 1.72 percent. Lanka Bangla Finance saw turnover worth Tk 152.858 million to rise 6.10 percent and closed at Tk 42. Among the other scrips on the turnover boardBextex Ltd, AB Bank, S Alam Cold Rolled Steels and Social Investment Bankfinished higher on buying pressure. Shinepukur Ceramics fell on profit-taking. Indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange finished higher paced by gains in leather, bank and real estate scrips. The CSCX or selective categories index gained 85.15 points or 1.60 percent to close at 5385.65. The CASPI or all share price index ended on 8300.83, surging 124.81 points or 1.52 percent. The CSE-30 blue chip shot up 164.88 points or 2.60 percent to finish at 6489.79. Of the traded issues, 95 advanced, 60 declined with twelve scrips holding steady. Beximco Ltd topped the turnover board, with shares worth Tk 85.54 million changing hands. Beximco Pharmaceuticals, AB Bank, Titas Gas and Lanka Bangla Finance were the other turnover leaders. Turnover on the port city's bourse rose to Tk 621.204 million from Tk 545.281 million from the previous day.
